gdom"},"nl":{"1192–":"1192–Overleden","1172–1236":"1172–1236","1192–Female":"1192–Overleden","1222–1280":"1222–1280","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1204–Female":"1204–Overleden","1218–1300":"1218–1300","–Male":"Overleden","1146–Male":"1146–Overleden","1155–Female":"1155–Overleden","1220":"1220","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1192":"1192","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1204":"1204","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","about 1218":"circa 1218","1146":"1146","1300":"1300","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","before 1192":"vóór 1192","1218":"1218","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Newtimber, Sussex, England":"Newtimber, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1192–":"1192–Deceased","1172–1236":"1172–1236","1192–Female":"1192–Deceased","1222–1280":"1222–1280","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1218–1300":"1218–1300","–Male":"Deceased","1146–Male":"1146–Deceased","1155–Female":"1155–Deceased","1220":"1220","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1192":"1192","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1204":"1204","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","about 1218":"about 1218","1146":"1146","1300":"1300","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","before 1192":"before 1192","1218":"1218","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Newtimber, Sussex, England":"Newtimber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nouwell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Noel  ,   Knowles  , or   Newell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nowels","meanings":["Altered form of   Nowell   or   Noel  , with the addition of excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Noel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Normand, Antoine, Jacques, Alphonse, Leonce, Lucien, Marcel, Damien, Emile, Francois.","French and Walloon (<b>Noël</b>); English: from the Old French personal name <i>Noël</i>, Middle English <i>Noel</i>, from Old French <i>no(u)el</i> ‘Christmas’ (from Latin <i>natalis (dies)</i> ‘birthday’), used for someone born during the Christmas period. Alternatively, a nickname for someone who had some special connection with the Christmas season, such as owing the particular feudal duty of providing a yule-log to the lord of the manor, or having given a memorable performance as the Lord of Misrule. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium. Compare   Christmas   and   Newell  .","English: sometimes a post-medieval variant of <b>Knowle</b> and   Knoll   (see   Knowles  ). The loss of /k/ before /n/ is known in everyday speech by the 17th century and may have been earlier."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":23,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":32,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":67,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":98,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Nouwell was born in 1192, in St Albans, Hertfordshire, England, her father, Geoffrey de Noel, was 46 and her mother, Benedicta Chaney, was 37. She married John de Cheyne. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in Newtimber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1192–":"1192–Surnud","1172–1236":"1172–1236","1192–Female":"1192–Surnud","1222–1280":"1222–1280","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1218–1300":"1218–1300","–Male":"Surnud","1146–Male":"1146–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1220":"1220","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1192":"1192","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1204":"1204","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","about 1218":"umbes 1218","1146":"1146","1300":"1300","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","before 1192":"enne 1192","1218":"1218","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St 